{"timestamp": "2025-12-05 05:31:25.342572", "event": "llm_start", "messages": "content=\"Based on the diagnosis report: Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\\n\\nScope and approach\\n- Validated end-to-end IP reachability, routing, DNS, and HTTP service access from representative user hosts.\\n- Probed key servers (DNS, web servers, load balancer) and inspected host configurations.\\n- Focused on detecting anomalies, localizing faulty devices, and identifying root causes without proposing remediation.\\n\\nKey observations (normal/healthy)\\n- OSPF/routing: End-to-end IP reachability across subnets is healthy. System-wide ping matrix shows 0% loss and low RTTs (≈1–5 ms typical) between hosts and servers, indicating working routing and properly advertised networks.\\n- DHCP: Hosts have valid leases and default routes via 10.x.x.1. Example: host_1_1_1_1 (10.1.1.21/24), host_2_1_1_1 (10.2.1.17/24).\\n- DNS:\\n  - Both hosts use 10.200.0.2 as resolver (/etc/resolv.conf).\\n  - Name resolution works for web0.local, web1.local, web2.local, web3.local, web99.local; A records map to 10.200.0.3–.7 as expected.\\n  - DNS server is listening on 10.200.0.2:53 (BIND), and name lookup latencies are low (a few ms).\\n- Load balancer (web99.local, 10.200.0.7):\\n  - Reachable from both hosts; HTTP requests complete reliably with total times ≈1.0–1.25 s. No errors observed.\\n\\nDetected anomalies\\n1) Web server 3 (web3.local, 10.200.0.6) is not serving as expected and times out for normal HTTP GETs from hosts.\\n   - From host_1_1_1_1 and host_2_1_1_1, multiple curl GET attempts to http://web3.local timed out (>10 s).\\n   - However, a HEAD request returns immediately:\\n     - HTTP/1.0 501 Unsupported method ('HEAD')\\n     - Server: BaseHTTP/0.6 Python/3.11.2\\n   - ICMP reachability to 10.200.0.6 is fine (0% loss, ~2–4 ms).\\n   - On web_server_3:\\n     - apache2.service is inactive (dead).\\n     - Port 80 is listening (netstat shows 0.0.0.0:80), consistent with a Python BaseHTTP server responding with 501 to HEAD.\\n     - iptables policy is ACCEPT (no filtering).\\n   - Effect: Application-layer behavior on web_server_3 is wrong (Apache expected; Python BaseHTTP present), and HTTP GETs from clients stall until curl timeout.\\n\\n2) Potential policy deviation: direct access to backend-like web servers from user subnets.\\n   - Hosts can directly reach and fetch content from web0.local, web1.local, and web2.local with normal latencies.\\n   - The stated design indicates the backend web servers should not be directly accessible from hosts. If web_server_0..2 are intended to be backend-only behind the load balancer, this exposure is a policy/control-plane issue. (If these are meant to be standalone public Apache servers, then this may be expected; the data provided doesn’t definitively disambiguate.)\\n\\nLocalization of faults\\n- The network underlay (switches, distribution, cores, OSPF) behaves normally: no loss, normal RTTs, valid routing, and working DNS.\\n- The anomaly is localized to the application/service on web_server_3:\\n  - Host: web_server_3 (10.200.0.6)\\n  - Service: HTTP on port 80 (Apache expected but not running; Python BaseHTTP present).\\n  - Not a transport/routing issue (ICMP reachability OK; sockets listening on 80 are present).\\n\\nRoot cause assessment\\n- Primary root cause: Misconfiguration or service failure on web_server_3.\\n  - Apache HTTP server (apache2) is stopped/inactive.\\n  - A Python BaseHTTP server is bound to port 80 instead, returning 501 to HEAD and causing GET requests from clients to hang/timeout.\\n  - No evidence of firewall or routing problems for this host.\\n- Secondary (conditional) root cause (if applicable per design intent): Lack of network-layer controls preventing direct user access to backend servers. Hosts can reach web0–web2 directly over OSPF, suggesting missing ACLs/firewall/isolation if those nodes are meant to be backend-only.\\n\\nImpact\\n- web3.local is effectively unusable for clients (HTTP GET timeouts), despite being reachable at IP level; service is down/misbehaving at the application layer.\\n- Load balancer web99.local is working; no immediate evidence it is sending traffic to web_server_3 (performance to web99 is stable). If web3 were in any balancing pool, client experience could intermittently fail unless LB has proper health checks excluding it.\\n- Broader network health is good; the issue is isolated to the web_server_3 HTTP service configuration., please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available.\" additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='21a78928-ce4a-4876-92b8-5ba0dd5120c5'", "model": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
